# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: wifi-security-wpa
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] For example, in IEEE 802.11 (Wi-Fi) the WPA and WPA2 standards have adopted IEEE 802.1X (with various EAP types) as the canonical authentication mechanism.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP is an authentication framework, not a specific authentication mechanism.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] It provides some common functions and negotiation of authentication methods called EAP methods.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] There are currently about 40 different methods defined.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] Methods defined in IETF RFCs include EAP-MD5, EAP-POTP, EAP-GTC, EAP-TLS, EAP-IKEv2, EAP-SIM, EAP-AKA, and EAP-AKA'.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] Additionally, a number of vendor-specific methods and new proposals exist.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] Commonly used modern methods capable of operating in wireless networks include EAP-TLS, EAP-SIM, EAP-AKA, LEAP and EAP-TTLS.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] Requirements for EAP methods used in wireless LAN authentication are described in RFC 4017.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] The list of type and packets codes used in EAP is available from the IANA EAP Registry.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] The standard also describes the conditions under which the AAA key management requirements described in RFC 4962 can be satisfied.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] The Lightweight Extensible Authentication Protocol (LEAP) method was developed by Cisco Systems prior to the IEEE ratification of the 802.11i security standard.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] Cisco distributed the protocol through the CCX (Cisco Certified Extensions) as part of getting 802.1X and dynamic WEP adoption into the industry in the absence of a standard.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] There is no native support for LEAP in any Windows operating system, but it is widely supported by third-party client software most commonly included with WLAN (wireless LAN) devices.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] LEAP support for Microsoft Windows 7 and Microsoft Windows Vista can be added by downloading a client add in from Cisco that provides support for both LEAP and EAP-FAST.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] Due to the wide adoption of LEAP in the networking industry many other WLAN vendors claim support for LEAP.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] LEAP uses a modified version of MS-CHAP, an authentication protocol in which user credentials are not strongly protected and easily compromised; an exploit tool called ASLEAP was released in early 2004 by Joshua Wright.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] Cisco recommends that customers who absolutely must use LEAP do so only with sufficiently complex passwords, though complex passwords are difficult to administer and enforce.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] Cisco's current recommendation is to use newer and stronger EAP protocols such as EAP-FAST, PEAP, or EAP-TLS.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP Transport Layer Security (EAP-TLS), defined in RFC 5216, is an IETF open standard that uses the Transport Layer Security (TLS) protocol, and is well-supported among wireless vendors.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-TLS is the original, standard wireless LAN EAP authentication protocol.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-TLS is still considered one of the most secure EAP standards available, although TLS provides strong security only as long as the user understands potential warnings about false credentials, and is universally supported by all manufacturers of wireless LAN hardware and software.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] Until April 2005, EAP-TLS was the only EAP type vendors needed to certify for a WPA or WPA2 logo.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] There are client and server implementations of EAP-TLS in 3Com, Apple, Avaya, Brocade Communications, Cisco, Enterasys Networks, Fortinet, Foundry, Hirschmann, HP, Juniper, Microsoft, and open source operating systems.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-TLS is natively supported in Mac OS X 10.3 and above, wpa_supplicant, Windows 2000 SP4, Windows XP and above, Windows Mobile 2003 and above, Windows CE 4.2, and Apple's iOS mobile operating system.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] Unlike most TLS implementations of HTTPS, such as on the World Wide Web, the majority of implementations of EAP-TLS require mutual authentication using client-side X.509 certificates without giving the option to disable the requirement, even though the standard does not mandate their use.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] Some have identified this as having the potential to dramatically reduce adoption of EAP-TLS and prevent "open" but encrypted access points.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] This would allow for situations much like HTTPS, where a wireless hotspot allows free access and does not authenticate station clients but station clients wish to use encryption (IEEE 802.11i-2004 i.e.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] WPA2) and potentially authenticate the wireless hotspot.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] There have also been proposals to use IEEE 802.11u for access points to signal that they allow EAP-TLS using only server-side authentication, using the standard EAP-TLS IETF type instead of a vendor-specific EAP type.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] The requirement for a client-side certificate, however unpopular it may be, is what gives EAP-TLS its authentication strength and illustrates the classic convenience vs. security trade-off.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] With a client-side certificate, a compromised password is not enough to break into EAP-TLS enabled systems because the intruder still needs to have the client-side certificate; indeed, a password is not even needed, as it is only used to encrypt the client-side certificate for storage.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] The highest security available is when the "private keys" of client-side certificate are housed in smart cards.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] This is because there is no way to steal a client-side certificate's corresponding private key from a smart card without stealing the card itself.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] It is more likely that the physical theft of a smart card would be noticed (and the smart card immediately revoked) than a (typical) password theft would be noticed.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] In addition, the private key on a smart card is typically encrypted using a PIN that only the owner of the smart card knows, minimizing its utility for a thief even before the card has been reported stolen and revoked.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-MD5 was the only IETF Standards Track based EAP method when it was first defined in the original RFC for EAP, RFC 2284.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] It offers minimal security; the MD5 hash function is vulnerable to dictionary attacks, and does not support key generation, which makes it unsuitable for use with dynamic WEP, or WPA/WPA2 enterprise.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-MD5 differs from other EAP methods in that it only provides authentication of the EAP peer to the EAP server but not mutual authentication.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] By not providing EAP server authentication, this EAP method is vulnerable to man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-MD5 support was first included in Windows 2000 and deprecated in Windows Vista.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP Protected One-Time Password (EAP-POTP), which is described in RFC 4793, is an EAP method developed by RSA Laboratories that uses one-time password (OTP) tokens, such as a handheld hardware device or a hardware or software module running on a personal computer, to generate authentication keys.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-POTP can be used to provide unilateral or mutual authentication and key material in protocols that use EAP.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] The EAP-POTP method provides two-factor user authentication, meaning that a user needs both physical access to a token and knowledge of a personal identification number (PIN) to perform authentication.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP Pre-shared key (EAP-PSK), defined in RFC 4764, is an EAP method for mutual authentication and session key derivation using a pre-shared key (PSK).
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] It provides a protected communication channel, when mutual authentication is successful, for both parties to communicate and is designed for authentication over insecure networks such as IEEE 802.11.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-PSK is documented in an experimental RFC that provides a lightweight and extensible EAP method that does not require any public-key cryptography.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] The EAP method protocol exchange is done in a minimum of four messages.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP Password (EAP-PWD), defined in RFC 5931, is an EAP method which uses a shared password for authentication.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] The password may be a low-entropy one and may be drawn from some set of possible passwords, like a dictionary, which is available to an attacker.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] The underlying key exchange is resistant to active attack, passive attack, and dictionary attack.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-PWD is in the base of Android 4.0 (ICS).
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] It is in FreeRADIUS and Radiator RADIUS servers, and it is in hostapd and wpa_supplicant.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP Tunneled Transport Layer Security (EAP-TTLS) is an EAP protocol that extends TLS.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] It was co-developed by Funk Software and Certicom and is widely supported across platforms.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] Microsoft did not incorporate native support for the EAP-TTLS protocol in Windows XP, Vista, or 7.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] Supporting TTLS on these platforms requires third-party Encryption Control Protocol (ECP) certified software.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] Microsoft Windows started EAP-TTLS support with Windows 8, support for EAP-TTLS appeared in Windows Phone version 8.1.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] The client can, but does not have to be authenticated via a CA-signed PKI certificate to the server.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] This greatly simplifies the setup procedure since a certificate is not needed on every client.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] After the server is securely authenticated to the client via its CA certificate and optionally the client to the server, the server can then use the established secure connection ("tunnel") to authenticate the client.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] It can use an existing and widely deployed authentication protocol and infrastructure, incorporating legacy password mechanisms and authentication databases, while the secure tunnel provides protection from eavesdropping and man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] Note that the user's name is never transmitted in unencrypted clear text, improving privacy.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] Two distinct versions of EAP-TTLS exist: original EAP-TTLS (a.k.a.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-TTLSv0 is described in RFC 5281, EAP-TTLSv1 is available as an Internet draft.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] 2 (EAP-IKEv2) is an EAP method based on the Internet Key Exchange protocol version 2 (IKEv2).
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] It provides mutual authentication and session key establishment between an EAP peer and an EAP server.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] bit strings that are known to both the server and the peer.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] High-entropy bit strings that are known to both the server and the peer.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] It is possible to use a different authentication credential (and thereby technique) in each direction.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] For example, the EAP server authenticates itself using public/private key pair and the EAP peer using symmetric key.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] However, not all of the nine theoretical combinations are expected in practice.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] Specifically, the standard RFC 5106 lists four use cases: The server authenticating with an asymmetric key pair while the client uses any of the three methods; and that both sides use a symmetric key.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-IKEv2 is described in RFC 5106, and a prototype implementation exists.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] Flexible Authentication via Secure Tunneling (EAP-FAST; RFC 4851) is a protocol proposal by Cisco Systems as a replacement for LEAP.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] The protocol was designed to address the weaknesses of LEAP while preserving the "lightweight" implementation.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] Use of server certificates is optional in EAP-FAST.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-FAST uses a Protected Access Credential (PAC) to establish a TLS tunnel in which client credentials are verified.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] When automatic PAC provisioning is enabled, EAP-FAST has a vulnerability where an attacker can intercept the PAC and use that to compromise user credentials.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] This vulnerability is mitigated by manual PAC provisioning or by using server certificates for the PAC provisioning phase.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] It is worth noting that the PAC file is issued on a per-user basis.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] This is a requirement in RFC 4851 sec 7.4.4 so if a new user logs on the network from a device, a new PAC file must be provisioned first.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] This is one reason why it is difficult not to run EAP-FAST in insecure anonymous provisioning mode.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] The alternative is to use device passwords instead, but then the device is validated on the network not the user.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-FAST can be used without PAC files, falling back to normal TLS.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-FAST is natively supported in Apple OS X 10.4.8 and newer.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] Cisco supplies an EAP-FAST module for Windows Vista and later operating systems which have an extensible EAPHost architecture for new authentication methods and supplicants.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] Tunnel Extensible Authentication Protocol (TEAP; RFC 7170) is a tunnel-based EAP method that enables secure communication between a peer and a server by using the Transport Layer Security (TLS) protocol to establish a mutually authenticated tunnel.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] Within the tunnel, TLV (Type-Length-Value) objects are used to convey authentication-related data between the EAP peer and the EAP server.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] In addition to peer authentication, TEAP allows the peer to ask the server for a certificate by sending a request in PKCS#10 format.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] After receiving the certificate request and authenticating the peer, the server can provision a certificate to the peer in PKCS#7 format (RFC 2325).
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] The server can also distribute trusted root certificates to the peer in PKCS#7 format (RFC 2325).
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] Both operations are enclosed into the corresponding TLVs and happen securely within the already established TLS tunnel.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP Subscriber Identity Module (EAP-SIM) is used for authentication and session key distribution using the subscriber identity module (SIM) from the Global System for Mobile Communications (GSM).
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] GSM cellular networks use a subscriber identity module card to carry out user authentication.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-SIM uses a SIM authentication algorithm between the client and an Authentication, Authorization and Accounting (AAA) server providing mutual authentication between the client and the network.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] In EAP-SIM the communication between the SIM card and the Authentication Centre (AuC) replaces the need for a pre-established password between the client and the AAA server.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] The A3/A8 algorithms are being run a few times, with different 128 bit challenges, so there will be more 64 bit Kc-s which will be combined/mixed to create stronger keys (Kc-s won't be used directly).
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] The lack of mutual authentication in GSM has also been overcome.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] Extensible Authentication Protocol Method for Universal Mobile Telecommunications System (UMTS) Authentication and Key Agreement (EAP-AKA), is an EAP mechanism for authentication and session key distribution using the UMTS Subscriber Identity Module (USIM).
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] The EAP-AKA' variant of EAP-AKA, defined in RFC 5448, and is used for non-3GPP access to a 3GPP core network.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP Generic Token Card, or EAP-GTC, is an EAP method created by Cisco as an alternative to PEAPv0/EAP-MSCHAPv2 and defined in RFC 2284 and RFC 3748.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-GTC carries a text challenge from the authentication server, and a reply generated by a security token.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] The PEAP-GTC authentication mechanism allows generic authentication to a number of databases such as Novell Directory Service (NDS) and Lightweight Directory Access Protocol (LDAP), as well as the use of a one-time password.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP with the encrypted key exchange, or EAP-EKE, is one of the few EAP methods that provide secure mutual authentication using short passwords and no need for public key certificates.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] It is a three-round exchange, based on the Diffie-Hellman variant of the well-known EKE protocol.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] Nimble out-of-band authentication for EAP (EAP-NOOB) is a generic bootstrapping solution for devices which have no pre-configured authentication credentials and which are not yet registered on any server.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] It is especially useful for Internet-of-Things (IoT) gadgets and toys that come with no information about any owner, network or server.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] Authentication for this EAP method is based on a user-assisted out-of-band (OOB) channel between the server and peer.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-NOOB supports many types of OOB channels such as QR codes, NFC tags, audio etc. and unlike other EAP methods, the protocol security has been verified by formal modeling of the specification with ProVerif and MCRL2 tools.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-NOOB performs an Ephemeral Elliptic Curve Diffie-Hellman (ECDHE) over the in-band EAP channel.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] The user then confirms this exchange by transferring the OOB message.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] Users can transfer the OOB message from the peer to the server, when for example, the device is a smart TV that can show a QR code.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] Alternatively, users can transfer the OOB message from the server to the peer, when for example, the device being bootstrapped is a camera that can only read a QR code.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP is not a wire protocol; instead it only defines message formats.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] Each protocol that uses EAP defines a way to encapsulate EAP messages within that protocol's messages.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] The encapsulation of EAP over IEEE 802 is defined in IEEE 802.1X and known as "EAP over LANs" or EAPOL.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAPOL was originally designed for IEEE 802.3 Ethernet in 802.1X-2001, but was clarified to suit other IEEE 802 LAN technologies such as IEEE 802.11 wireless and Fiber Distributed Data Interface (ANSI X3T9.5/X3T12, adopted as ISO 9314) in 802.1X-2004.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] The EAPOL protocol was also modified for use with IEEE 802.1AE (MACsec) and IEEE 802.1AR (Initial Device Identity, IDevID) in 802.1X-2010.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] The Protected Extensible Authentication Protocol, also known as Protected EAP or simply PEAP, is a protocol that encapsulates EAP within a potentially encrypted and authenticated Transport Layer Security (TLS) tunnel.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] The purpose was to correct deficiencies in EAP; EAP assumed a protected communication channel, such as that provided by physical security, so facilities for protection of the EAP conversation were not provided.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] PEAP was jointly developed by Cisco Systems, Microsoft, and RSA Security.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] PEAPv0 was the version included with Microsoft Windows XP and was nominally defined in draft-kamath-pppext-peapv0-00.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] PEAPv1 and PEAPv2 were defined in different versions of *draft-josefsson-pppext-eap-tls-eap*.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] PEAPv1 was defined in draft-josefsson-pppext-eap-tls-eap-00 through draft-josefsson-pppext-eap-tls-eap-05, and PEAPv2 was defined in versions beginning with draft-josefsson-pppext-eap-tls-eap-06.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] The protocol only specifies chaining multiple EAP mechanisms and not any specific method.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] Use of the EAP-MSCHAPv2 and EAP-GTC methods are the most commonly supported.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] Both the RADIUS and Diameter AAA protocols can encapsulate EAP messages.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] They are often used by Network Access Server (NAS) devices to forward EAP packets between IEEE 802.1X endpoints and AAA servers to facilitate IEEE 802.1X.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] The Protocol for Carrying Authentication for Network Access (PANA) is an IP-based protocol that allows a device to authenticate itself with a network to be granted access.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] PANA will not define any new authentication protocol, key distribution, key agreement or key derivation protocols; for these purposes, EAP will be used, and PANA will carry the EAP payload.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] PANA allows dynamic service provider selection, supports various authentication methods, is suitable for roaming users, and is independent from the link layer mechanisms.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP was originally an authentication extension for the Point-to-Point Protocol (PPP).
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] PPP has supported EAP since EAP was created as an alternative to the Challenge-Handshake Authentication Protocol (CHAP) and the Password Authentication Protocol (PAP), which were eventually incorporated into EAP.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/extensible-authentication-protocol] The EAP extension to PPP was first defined in RFC 2284, now obsoleted by RFC 3748.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-11i-2004] 802.11i supersedes the previous security specification, Wired Equivalent Privacy (WEP), which was shown to have security vulnerabilities.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-11i-2004] Wi-Fi Protected Access (WPA) had previously been introduced by the Wi-Fi Alliance as an intermediate solution to WEP insecurities.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-11i-2004] WPA implemented a subset of a draft of 802.11i.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-11i-2004] The Wi-Fi Alliance refers to their approved, interoperable implementation of the full 802.11i as **WPA2**, also called **RSN** (Robust Security Network).
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-11i-2004] 802.11i makes use of the Advanced Encryption Standard (AES) block cipher, whereas WEP and WPA use the RC4 stream cipher.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-11i-2004] IEEE 802.11i enhances IEEE 802.11-1999 by providing a Robust Security Network (RSN) with two new protocols: the four-way handshake and the group key handshake.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-11i-2004] These utilize the authentication services and port access control described in IEEE 802.1X to establish and change the appropriate cryptographic keys.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-11i-2004] The RSN is a security network that only allows the creation of robust security network associations (RSNAs), which are a type of association used by a pair of stations (STAs) if the procedure to establish authentication or association between them includes the 4-Way Handshake.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-11i-2004] The standard also provides two RSNA data confidentiality and integrity protocols, TKIP and CCMP, with implementation of CCMP being mandatory since the confidentiality and integrity mechanisms of TKIP are not as robust as those of CCMP.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-11i-2004] The main purpose to implement TKIP was that the algorithm should be implementable within the capabilities of most of the old devices supporting only WEP.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-11i-2004] The initial authentication process is carried out either using a pre-shared key (PSK), or following an EAP exchange through 802.1X (known as EAPOL, which requires the presence of an authentication server).
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-11i-2004] This process ensures that the client station (STA) is authenticated with the access point (AP).
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-11i-2004] After the PSK or 802.1X authentication, a shared secret key is generated, called the Pairwise Master Key (PMK).
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-11i-2004] In PSK authentication, the PMK is actually the PSK, which is typically derived from the WiFi password by putting it through a key derivation function that uses SHA-1 as the cryptographic hash function.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-11i-2004] If an 802.1X EAP exchange was carried out, the PMK is derived from the EAP parameters provided by the authentication server.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-11i-2004] The four-way handshake is designed so that the access point (or authenticator) and wireless client (or supplicant) can independently prove to each other that they know the PSK/PMK, without ever disclosing the key.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-11i-2004] Instead of disclosing the key, the access point (AP) and client encrypt messages to each other—that can only be decrypted by using the PMK that they already share—and if decryption of the messages was successful, this proves knowledge of the PMK.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-11i-2004] The four-way handshake is critical for protection of the PMK from malicious access points—for example, an attacker's SSID impersonating a real access point—so that the client never has to tell the access point its PMK.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-11i-2004] The PMK is designed to last the entire session and should be exposed as little as possible; therefore, keys to encrypt the traffic need to be derived.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-11i-2004] A four-way handshake is used to establish another key called the Pairwise Transient Key (PTK).
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-11i-2004] The PTK is generated by concatenating the following attributes: PMK, AP nonce (ANonce), STA nonce (SNonce), AP MAC address, and STA MAC address.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-11i-2004] The product is then put through a pseudo-random function.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-11i-2004] The handshake also yields the GTK (Group Temporal Key), used to decrypt multicast and broadcast traffic.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-11i-2004] The STA sends its own nonce-value (SNonce) to the AP together with a Message Integrity Code (MIC), including authentication, which is really a Message Authentication and Integrity Code (MAIC), and the Key Replay Counter which will be the same as Message 1, to allow AP to match the right Message 1.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-11i-2004] The AP verifies Message 2, by checking MIC, RSN, ANonce and Key Replay Counter Field, and if valid constructs and sends the GTK with another MIC.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-11i-2004] The STA verifies Message 3, by checking MIC and Key Replay Counter Field, and if valid sends a confirmation to the AP.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-11i-2004] The Group Temporal Key (GTK) used in the network may need to be updated due to the expiration of a preset timer.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-11i-2004] When a device leaves the network, the GTK also needs to be updated.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-11i-2004] This is to prevent the device from receiving any more multicast or broadcast messages from the AP.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-11i-2004] The STA acknowledges the new GTK and replies to the AP.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-11i-2004] CCMP is based on the Counter with CBC-MAC (CCM) mode of the AES encryption algorithm.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-11i-2004] CCM combines CTR for confidentiality and CBC-MAC for authentication and integrity.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-11i-2004] CCM protects the integrity of both the MPDU Data field and selected portions of the IEEE 802.11 MPDU header.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-11i-2004] The pairwise key hierarchy utilizes PRF-384 or PRF-512 to derive session-specific keys from a PMK, generating a PTK, which gets partitioned into a KCK and a KEK plus all the temporal keys used by the MAC to protect unicast communication.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-11i-2004] The GTK shall be a random number which also gets generated by using PRF-n, usually PRF-128 or PRF-256, in this model, the group key hierarchy takes a GMK (Group Master Key) and generates a GTK.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-11i-2004] "The Protected Frame field is 1 bit in length.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-11i-2004] The Protected Frame field is set to 1 if the Frame Body field contains information that has been processed by a cryptographic encapsulation algorithm.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-11i-2004] The Protected Frame field is set to 1 only within data frames of type Data and within management frames of type Management, subtype Authentication.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-11i-2004] The Protected Frame field is set to 0 in all other frames.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-11i-2004] When the bit Protected Frame field is set to 1 in a data frame, the Frame Body field is protected utilizing the cryptographic encapsulation algorithm and expanded as defined in Clause 8.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] The standard directly addresses an attack technique called Hardware Addition where an attacker posing as a guest, customer or staff smuggles a hacking device into the building that they then plug into the network giving them full access.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] A notable example of the issue occurred in 2005 when a machine attached to Walmart's network hacked thousands of their servers.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] IEEE 802.1X defines the encapsulation of the Extensible Authentication Protocol (EAP) over wired IEEE 802 networks and over 802.11 wireless networks, which is known as "EAP over LAN" or EAPOL.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] EAPOL was originally specified for IEEE 802.3 Ethernet, IEEE 802.5 Token Ring, and FDDI (ANSI X3T9.5/X3T12 and ISO 9314) in 802.1X-2001, but was extended to suit other IEEE 802 LAN technologies such as IEEE 802.11 wireless in 802.1X-2004.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] The EAPOL was also modified for use with IEEE 802.1AE ("MACsec") and IEEE 802.1AR (Secure Device Identity, DevID) in 802.1X-2010 to support service identification and optional point to point encryption over the internal LAN segment.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] 802.1X is part of the logical link control (LLC) sublayer of the 802 reference model.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] 802.1X authentication involves three parties: a supplicant, an authenticator, and an authentication server.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] The **supplicant** is a client device (such as a laptop) that wishes to attach to the LAN/WLAN.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] The term 'supplicant' is also used interchangeably to refer to the software running on the client that provides credentials to the authenticator.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] Authentication servers typically run software supporting the RADIUS and EAP protocols.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] In some cases, the authentication server software may be running on the authenticator hardware.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] The authenticator acts like a security guard to a protected network.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] The supplicant (i.e., client device) is not allowed access through the authenticator to the protected side of the network until the supplicant's identity has been validated and authorized.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] With 802.1X port-based authentication, the supplicant must initially provide the required credentials to the authenticator - these will have been specified in advance by the network administrator and could include a user name/password or a permitted digital certificate.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] The authenticator forwards these credentials to the authentication server to decide whether access is to be granted.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] If the authentication server determines the credentials are valid, it informs the authenticator, which in turn allows the supplicant (client device) to access resources located on the protected side of the network.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] EAPOL operates over the data link layer, and in Ethernet II framing protocol has an EtherType value of 0x888E.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] 802.1X-2001 defines two logical port entities for an authenticated port—the "controlled port" and the "uncontrolled port".
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] The controlled port is manipulated by the 802.1X PAE (Port Access Entity) to allow (in the authorized state) or prevent (in the unauthorized state) network traffic ingress and egress to/from the controlled port.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] The uncontrolled port is used by the 802.1X PAE to transmit and receive EAPOL frames.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] 802.1X-2004 defines the equivalent port entities for the supplicant; so a supplicant implementing 802.1X-2004 may prevent higher-level protocols from being used if it is not content that authentication has successfully completed.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] This is particularly useful when an EAP method providing mutual authentication is used, as the supplicant can prevent data leakage when connected to an unauthorized network.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] **Initiation** To initiate authentication the authenticator will periodically transmit EAP-Request Identity frames to a special Layer 2 MAC address (*01:80:C2:00:00:03*) on the local network segment.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] The supplicant listens at this address, and on receipt of the EAP-Request Identity frame, it responds with an EAP-Response Identity frame containing an identifier for the supplicant such as a User ID.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] The authenticator then encapsulates this Identity response in a RADIUS Access-Request packet and forwards it on to the authentication server.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] The supplicant may also initiate or restart authentication by sending an EAPOL-Start frame to the authenticator, which will then reply with an EAP-Request Identity frame.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] **Negotiation** *(Technically EAP negotiation)* The authentication server sends a reply (encapsulated in a RADIUS Access-Challenge packet) to the authenticator, containing an EAP Request specifying the EAP Method (The type of EAP based authentication it wishes the supplicant to perform).
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] The authenticator encapsulates the EAP Request in an EAPOL frame and transmits it to the supplicant.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] At this point, the supplicant can start using the requested EAP Method, or do a NAK ("Negative Acknowledgement") and respond with the EAP Methods it is willing to perform.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] If authentication is successful, the authenticator sets the port to the "authorized" state and normal traffic is allowed.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] If it is unsuccessful, the port remains in the "unauthorized" state.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] When the supplicant logs off, it sends an EAPOL-logoff message to the authenticator, the authenticator then sets the port to the "unauthorized" state, once again blocking all non-EAP traffic.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] An open-source project named Open1X produces a client, Xsupplicant.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] This client is currently available for both Linux and Windows.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] The main drawbacks of the Open1X client are that it does not provide comprehensible and extensive user documentation and that most Linux vendors do not provide a package for it.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] The more general wpa_supplicant can be used for 802.11 wireless networks and wired networks.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] Both support a very wide range of EAP types.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] ChromeOS has supported 802.1X since mid-2011.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] Avenda Systems provides a supplicant for Windows, Linux and macOS.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] They also have a plugin for the Microsoft NAP framework.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] Avenda also offers health checking agents.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] Windows defaults to not responding to 802.1X authentication requests for 20 minutes after a failed authentication.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] This can cause significant disruption to clients.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] The block period can be configured using the HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\dot3svc\BlockTime DWORD value (HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\wlansvc\BlockTime for wireless networks) in the registry (entered in minutes).
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] A hotfix is required for Windows XP SP3 and Windows Vista SP2 to make the period configurable.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] Wildcard server certificates are not supported by EAPHost, the Windows component that provides EAP support in the operating system.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] The implication of this is that when using a commercial certification authority, individual certificates must be purchased.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] Windows XP has major issues with its handling of IP address changes resulting from user-based 802.1X authentication that changes the VLAN and thus subnet of clients.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] Microsoft has stated that it will not backport the SSO feature from Vista that resolves these issues.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] If users are not logging in with roaming profiles, a hotfix must be downloaded and installed if authenticating via PEAP with PEAP-MSCHAPv2.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] Windows Vista-based computers that are connected via an IP phone may not authenticate as expected and, as a result, the client can be placed into the wrong VLAN.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] Windows 7 based computers that are connected via an IP phone may not authenticate as expected and, consequently, the client can be placed into the wrong VLAN.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] Windows 7 does not respond to 802.1X authentication requests after initial 802.1X authentication fails.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] Windows PE does not have native support for 802.1X.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] However, support can be added to WinPE 2.1 and WinPE 3.0 through hotfixes that are available from Microsoft.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] Although full documentation is not yet available, preliminary documentation for the use of these hotfixes is available via a Microsoft blog.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] Most Linux distributions support 802.1X via wpa_supplicant and desktop integration like NetworkManager.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] The iPhone and iPod Touch support 802.1X since the release of iOS 2.0. macOS has offered native support since Mac OS X Panther.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] As of iOS 17 and macOS 14, Apple devices support connecting to 802.1X networks using EAP-TLS with TLS 1.3 (EAP-TLS 1.3).
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] Additionally, devices running iOS/iPadOS/tvOS 17 or later support wired 802.1X networks.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] Android has support for 802.1X since the release of 1.6 Donut.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] eduroam (the international roaming service), mandates the use of 802.1X authentication when providing network access to guests visiting from other eduroam-enabled institutions.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] BT (British Telecom, PLC) employs Identity Federation for authentication in services delivered to a wide variety of industries and governments.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] Not all devices support 802.1X authentication.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] Examples include network printers, Ethernet-based electronics like environmental sensors, cameras, and wireless phones.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] For those devices to be used in a protected network environment, alternative mechanisms must be provided to authenticate them.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] One option would be to disable 802.1X on that port, but that leaves that port unprotected and open for abuse.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] Another slightly more reliable option is to use the MAB option.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] When MAB is configured on a port, that port will first try to check if the connected device is 802.1X compliant, and if no reaction is received from the connected device, it will try to authenticate with the AAA server using the connected device's MAC address as username and password.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] The network administrator then must make provisions on the RADIUS server to authenticate those MAC addresses, either by adding them as regular users or implementing additional logic to resolve them in a network inventory database.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] Many managed Ethernet switches offer options for this.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] In the summer of 2005, Microsoft's Steve Riley posted an article (based on the original research of Microsoft MVP Svyatoslav Pidgorny) detailing a serious vulnerability in the 802.1X protocol, involving a man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] Riley suggests that for wired networks the use of IPsec or a combination of IPsec and 802.1X would be more secure.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] EAPOL-Logoff frames transmitted by the 802.1X supplicant are sent in the clear and contain no data derived from the credential exchange that initially authenticated the client.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] They are therefore trivially easy to spoof on shared media and can be used as part of a targeted DoS on both wired and wireless LANs.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] In an EAPOL-Logoff attack, a malicious third party with access to the medium the authenticator is attached to repeatedly sends forged EAPOL-Logoff frames from the target device's MAC Address.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] The authenticator (believing that the targeted device wishes to end its authentication session) closes the target's authentication session, blocking traffic ingressing from the target, denying it access to the network.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] The 802.1X-2010 specification, which began as 802.1af, addresses vulnerabilities in previous 802.1X specifications, by using MACsec IEEE 802.1AE to encrypt data between logical ports (running on top of a physical port) and IEEE 802.1AR (Secure Device Identity / DevID) authenticated devices.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] As a stopgap, until these enhancements are widely implemented, some vendors have extended the 802.1X-2001 and 802.1X-2004 protocol, allowing multiple concurrent authentication sessions to occur on a single port.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] While this prevents traffic from devices with unauthenticated MAC addresses ingressing on an 802.1X authenticated port, it will not stop a malicious device snooping on traffic from an authenticated device and provides no protection against MAC spoofing, or EAPOL-Logoff attacks.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/ieee-802-1x] The IETF-backed alternative is the Protocol for Carrying Authentication for Network Access (PANA), which also carries EAP, although it works at layer 3, using UDP, thus not being tied to the 802 infrastructure.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] WPA (sometimes referred to as the TKIP standard) became available in 2003.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] The Wi-Fi Alliance intended it as an intermediate measure in anticipation of the availability of the more secure and complex WPA2, which became available in 2004 and is a common shorthand for the full IEEE 802.11i (or IEEE 802.11i-2004) standard.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] In January 2018, the Wi-Fi Alliance announced the release of WPA3, which has several security improvements over WPA2.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] As of 2023, most computers that connect to a wireless network have support for using WPA, WPA2, or WPA3.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] WEP (Wired Equivalent Privacy) is an early encryption protocol for wireless networks, designed to secure WLAN connections.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] It supports 64-bit and 128-bit keys, combining user-configurable and factory-set bits.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] WEP uses the RC4 algorithm for encrypting data, creating a unique key for each packet by combining a new Initialization Vector (IV) with a shared key (it has 40 bits of vectored key and 24 bits of random numbers).
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Decryption involves reversing this process, using the IV and the shared key to generate a key stream and decrypt the payload.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Despite its initial use, WEP's significant vulnerabilities led to the adoption of more secure protocols.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] The Wi-Fi Alliance intended WPA as an intermediate measure to take the place of WEP pending the availability of the full IEEE 802.11 standard.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] WPA could be implemented through firmware upgrades on wireless network interface cards designed for WEP that began shipping as far back as 1999.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] However, since the changes required in the wireless access points (APs) were more extensive than those needed on the network cards, most pre-2003 APs were not upgradable by vendor-provided methods to support WPA.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] The WPA protocol implements the Temporal Key Integrity Protocol (TKIP).
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] WEP uses a 64-bit or 128-bit encryption key that must be manually entered on wireless access points and devices and does not change.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] TKIP employs a per-packet key, meaning that it dynamically generates a new 128-bit key for each packet and thus prevents the types of attacks that compromise WEP.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] WPA also includes a Message Integrity Check, which is designed to prevent an attacker from altering and resending data packets.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] This replaces the cyclic redundancy check (CRC) that was used by the WEP standard.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] CRC's main flaw is that it does not provide a sufficiently strong data integrity guarantee for the packets it handles.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Well-tested message authentication codes existed to solve these problems, but they require too much computation to be used on old network cards.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Researchers have since discovered a flaw in WPA that relied on older weaknesses in WEP and the limitations of the message integrity code hash function, named *Michael*, to retrieve the key-stream from short packets to use for re-injection and spoofing.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] WPA2, which requires testing and certification by the Wi-Fi Alliance, implements the mandatory elements of IEEE 802.11i.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] In particular, it includes support for CCMP, an AES-based encryption mode.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] From March 13, 2006, to June 30, 2020, WPA2 certification was mandatory for all new devices to bear the Wi-Fi trademark.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] In WPA2-protected WLANs, secure communication is established through a multi-step process.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Initially, devices associate with the Access Point (AP) via an association request.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] This is followed by a 4-way handshake, a crucial step for ensuring both the client and AP have the correct Pre-Shared Key (PSK) without actually transmitting it.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] During this handshake, a Pairwise Transient Key (PTK) is generated for secure data exchange.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] WPA2 employs the Advanced Encryption Standard (AES) with a 128-bit key, enhancing security through the Counter-Mode/CBC-Mac Protocol CCMP.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] This protocol ensures robust encryption and data integrity, using different Initialization Vectors (IVs) for encryption and authentication purposes.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Post-handshake, the established PTK is used for encrypting unicast traffic, and the Group Temporal Key (GTK) is used for broadcast traffic.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] This comprehensive authentication and encryption mechanism is what makes WPA2 a robust security standard for wireless networks.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] In January 2018, the Wi-Fi Alliance announced WPA3 as a replacement to WPA2.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Certification began in June 2018, and WPA3 support has been mandatory for devices which bear the "Wi-Fi CERTIFIED™" logo since July 2020.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] The new standard uses an equivalent 192-bit cryptographic strength in WPA3-Enterprise mode (AES-256 in GCM mode with SHA-384 as HMAC), and still mandates the use of CCMP-128 (AES-128 in CCM mode) as the minimum encryption algorithm in WPA3-Personal mode.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] The WPA3 standard also replaces the pre-shared key (PSK) exchange with Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE) exchange, a method originally introduced with IEEE 802.11s, resulting in a more secure initial key exchange in personal mode and forward secrecy.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] The Wi-Fi Alliance also says that WPA3 will mitigate security issues posed by weak passwords and simplify the process of setting up devices with no display interface.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] WPA3 also supports Opportunistic Wireless Encryption (OWE) for open Wi-Fi networks that do not have passwords.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] The Wi-Fi Alliance calls OWE "Wi-Fi CERTIFIED Enhanced Open"; Wi-Fi manufacturers often refer to it as "Enhanced Open" rather than OWE.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Protection of management frames as specified in the IEEE 802.11w amendment is also enforced by the WPA3 specifications.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] WPA has been designed specifically to work with wireless hardware produced prior to the introduction of the WPA protocol, which provide inadequate security through WEP.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Some of these devices support WPA only after applying firmware upgrades, which are not available for some legacy devices.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Wi-Fi devices certified since 2006 support both the WPA and WPA2 security protocols.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Different WPA versions and protection mechanisms can be distinguished based on the target end-user (such as WEP, WPA, WPA2, WPA3) and the method of authentication key distribution, as well as the encryption protocol used.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] As of July 2020, WPA3 is the latest iteration of the WPA standard, bringing enhanced security features and addressing vulnerabilities found in WPA2.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] WPA3 improves authentication methods and employs stronger encryption protocols, making it the recommended choice for securing Wi-Fi networks.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Also referred to as *WPA-PSK* (pre-shared key) mode, this is designed for home, small office and basic uses and does not require an authentication server.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Each wireless network device encrypts the network traffic by using its 128-bit encryption key obtained during the Temporal Key Integrity Protocol keys derivation from a 256-bit shared key.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] This key may be entered either as a string of 64 hexadecimal digits, or as a passphrase of 8 to 63 printable ASCII characters.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] This pass-phrase-to-PSK mapping is nevertheless not binding, as Annex J is informative in the latest 802.11 standard.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] If ASCII characters are used, the 256-bit key is calculated by applying the PBKDF2 key derivation function to the passphrase, using the SSID as the salt and 4096 iterations of HMAC-SHA1.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] WPA-Personal mode is available on all three WPA versions.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] This enterprise mode uses an 802.1X server for authentication, offering higher security control by replacing the vulnerable WEP with the more advanced TKIP encryption.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] TKIP ensures continuous renewal of encryption keys, reducing security risks.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Authentication is conducted through a RADIUS server, providing robust security, especially vital in corporate settings.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] This setup allows integration with Windows login processes and supports various authentication methods like Extensible Authentication Protocol, which uses certificates for secure authentication, and PEAP, creating a protected environment for authentication without requiring client certificates.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] stream cipher is used with a 128-bit per-packet key, meaning that it dynamically generates a new key for each packet.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] , though not all implementations enforce this.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Otherwise, the data rate will not exceed 54 Mbit/s.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Originally, only EAP-TLS (Extensible Authentication Protocol - Transport Layer Security) was certified by the Wi-Fi alliance.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] In April 2010, the Wi-Fi Alliance announced the inclusion of additional EAP types to its WPA- and WPA2-Enterprise certification programs.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] This was to ensure that WPA-Enterprise certified products can interoperate with one another.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] 802.1X clients and servers developed by specific firms may support other EAP types.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] This certification is an attempt for popular EAP types to interoperate; their failure to do so as of 2013 is one of the major issues preventing rollout of 802.1X on heterogeneous networks.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Commercial 802.1X servers include Microsoft Network Policy Server and Juniper Networks Steelbelted RADIUS as well as Aradial Radius server.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] FreeRADIUS is an open source 802.1X server.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] WPA-Personal and WPA2-Personal remain vulnerable to password cracking attacks if users rely on a weak password or passphrase.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] WPA passphrase hashes are seeded from the SSID name and its length; rainbow tables exist for the top 1,000 network SSIDs and a multitude of common passwords, requiring only a quick lookup to speed up cracking WPA-PSK.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Brute forcing of simple passwords can be attempted using the Aircrack Suite starting from the four-way authentication handshake exchanged during association or periodic re-authentication.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] WPA3 replaces cryptographic protocols susceptible to off-line analysis with protocols that require interaction with the infrastructure for each guessed password, supposedly placing temporal limits on the number of guesses.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] However, design flaws in WPA3 enable attackers to plausibly launch brute-force attacks .
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] WPA and WPA2 do not provide forward secrecy, meaning that once an adverse person discovers the pre-shared key, they can potentially decrypt all packets encrypted using that PSK transmitted in the future and even past, which could be passively and silently collected by the attacker.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] This also means an attacker can silently capture and decrypt others' packets if a WPA-protected access point is provided free of charge at a public place, because its password is usually shared to anyone in that place.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] In other words, WPA only protects from attackers who do not have access to the password.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Because of that, it's safer to use Transport Layer Security (TLS) or similar on top of that for the transfer of any sensitive data.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] However starting from WPA3, this issue has been addressed.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] In 2013, Mathy Vanhoef and Frank Piessens significantly improved upon the WPA-TKIP attacks of Erik Tews and Martin Beck.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] They demonstrated how to inject an arbitrary number of packets, with each packet containing at most 112 bytes of payload.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] This was demonstrated by implementing a port scanner, which can be executed against any client using WPA-TKIP.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Additionally, they showed how to decrypt arbitrary packets sent to a client.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] They mentioned this can be used to hijack a TCP connection, allowing an attacker to inject malicious JavaScript when the victim visits a website.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] In contrast, the Beck-Tews attack could only decrypt short packets with mostly known content, such as ARP messages, and only allowed injection of 3 to 7 packets of at most 28 bytes.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] The Beck-Tews attack also requires quality of service (as defined in 802.11e) to be enabled, while the Vanhoef-Piessens attack does not.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Neither attack leads to recovery of the shared session key between the client and Access Point.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] The authors say using a short rekeying interval can prevent some attacks but not all, and strongly recommend switching from TKIP to AES-based CCMP.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Halvorsen and others show how to modify the Beck-Tews attack to allow injection of 3 to 7 packets having a size of at most 596 bytes.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] The downside is that their attack requires substantially more time to execute: approximately 18 minutes and 25 seconds.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] In other work Vanhoef and Piessens showed that, when WPA is used to encrypt broadcast packets, their original attack can also be executed.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] This is an important extension, as substantially more networks use WPA to protect broadcast packets, than to protect unicast packets.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] The execution time of this attack is on average around 7 minutes, compared to the 14 minutes of the original Vanhoef-Piessens and Beck-Tews attack.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] The vulnerabilities of TKIP are significant because WPA-TKIP had been held before to be an extremely safe combination; indeed, WPA-TKIP is still a configuration option upon a wide variety of wireless routing devices provided by many hardware vendors.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] A survey in 2013 showed that 71% still allow usage of TKIP, and 19% exclusively support TKIP.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] A more serious security flaw, revealed in December 2011 by Stefan Viehböck, is the production that affects wireless routers with the Wi-Fi Protected Setup (WPS) feature, regardless of which encryption method they use.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Most recent models have this feature and enable it by default.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Many consumer Wi-Fi device manufacturers had taken steps to eliminate the potential of weak passphrase choices by promoting alternative methods of automatically generating and distributing strong keys when users add a new wireless adapter or appliance to a network.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] These methods include pushing buttons on the devices or entering an 8-digit PIN.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] The Wi-Fi Alliance standardized these methods as Wi-Fi Protected Setup; however, the PIN feature as widely implemented introduced a major new security flaw.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] The flaw allows a remote attacker to recover the WPS PIN and, with it, the router's WPA/WPA2 password in a few hours.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Users have been urged to turn off the WPS feature, although this may not be possible on some router models.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Also, the PIN is written on a label on most Wi-Fi routers with WPS, which cannot be changed if compromised.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] In 2018, the Wi-Fi Alliance introduced Wi-Fi Easy Connect as a new alternative for the configuration of devices that lack sufficient user interface capabilities by allowing nearby devices to serve as an adequate UI for network provisioning purposes, thus mitigating the need for WPS.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Several weaknesses have been found in MS-CHAPv2, some of which severely reduce the complexity of brute-force attacks, making them feasible with modern hardware.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] In 2012 the complexity of breaking MS-CHAPv2 was reduced to that of breaking a single DES key (work by Moxie Marlinspike and Marsh Ray).
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Tunneled EAP methods using TTLS or PEAP which encrypt the MSCHAPv2 exchange are widely deployed to protect against exploitation of this vulnerability.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] However, prevalent WPA2 client implementations during the early 2000s were prone to misconfiguration by end users, or in some cases (e.g.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Android), lacked any user-accessible way to properly configure validation of AAA server certificate CNs.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] This extended the relevance of the original weakness in MSCHAPv2 within MiTM attack scenarios.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Under stricter compliance tests for WPA2 announced alongside WPA3, certified client software will be required to conform to certain behaviors surrounding AAA certificate validation.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Hole196 is a vulnerability in the WPA2 protocol that abuses the shared Group Temporal Key (GTK).
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] It can be used to conduct man-in-the-middle and denial-of-service attacks.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] However, it assumes that the attacker is already authenticated against Access Point and thus in possession of the GTK.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] In 2016 it was shown that the WPA and WPA2 standards contain a proposed example random number generator (RNG) that is insecure.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Researchers showed that, if vendors implement the proposed RNG, an attacker is able to predict the group key (GTK) that is supposed to be randomly generated by the access point (AP).
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Additionally, they showed that possession of the GTK enables the attacker to inject any traffic into the network, and allowed the attacker to decrypt unicast internet traffic transmitted over the wireless network.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] They demonstrated their attack against an Asus RT-AC51U router that uses the MediaTek out-of-tree drivers, which generate the GTK themselves, and showed the GTK can be recovered within two minutes or less.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Similarly, they demonstrated the keys generated by Broadcom access daemons running on VxWorks 5 and later can be recovered in four minutes or less, which affects, for example, certain versions of Linksys WRT54G and certain Apple AirPort Extreme models.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Vendors can defend against this attack by using a secure RNG.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] By doing so, Hostapd running on Linux kernels is not vulnerable against this attack and thus routers running typical OpenWrt or LEDE installations do not exhibit this issue.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] In October 2017, details of the KRACK (Key Reinstallation Attack) attack on WPA2 were published.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] The KRACK attack is believed to affect all variants of WPA and WPA2; however, the security implications vary between implementations, depending upon how individual developers interpreted a poorly specified part of the standard.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Software patches can resolve the vulnerability but are not available for all devices.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] KRACK exploits a weakness in the WPA2 4-Way Handshake, a critical process for generating encryption keys.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Attackers can force multiple handshakes, manipulating key resets.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] By intercepting the handshake, they could decrypt network traffic without cracking encryption directly.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] This poses a risk, especially with sensitive data transmission.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Manufacturers have released patches in response, but not all devices have received updates.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Users are advised to keep their devices updated to mitigate such security risks.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Regular updates are crucial for maintaining network security against evolving threats.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] In April 2019, the Dragonblood attacks exposed significant vulnerabilities in the Dragonfly handshake protocol used in WPA3 and EAP-pwd.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] These included side-channel attacks potentially revealing sensitive user information and implementation weaknesses in EAP-pwd and SAE.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Concerns were also raised about the inadequate security in transitional modes supporting both WPA2 and WPA3.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] In response, security updates and protocol changes are being integrated into WPA3 and EAP-pwd to address these vulnerabilities and enhance overall Wi-Fi security.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] In May 2021 FragAttacks, a set of new security vulnerabilities, were revealed, affecting Wi-Fi devices and enabling attackers within range to steal information or target devices.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] These include design flaws in the Wi-Fi standard, affecting most devices, and programming errors in Wi-Fi products, making almost all Wi-Fi products vulnerable.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] The vulnerabilities impact all Wi-Fi security protocols, including WPA3 and WEP.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Exploiting these flaws is complex but programming errors in Wi-Fi products are easier to exploit.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] Despite improvements in Wi-Fi security, these findings highlight the need for continuous security analysis and updates.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wi-fi-protected-access] In response, security patches were developed, and users are advised to use HTTPS and install available updates for protection.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] In 2003, the Wi-Fi Alliance announced that WEP and WEP2 had been superseded by Wi-Fi Protected Access (WPA).
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] In 2004, with the ratification of the full 802.11i standard (i.e.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] WPA2), the IEEE declared that both WEP-40 and WEP-104 have been deprecated.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] WPA retained some design characteristics of WEP that remained problematic.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] WEP was the only encryption protocol available to 802.11a and 802.11b devices built before the WPA standard, which was available for 802.11g devices.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] However, some 802.11b devices were later provided with firmware or software updates to enable WPA, and newer devices had it built in.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] WEP was ratified as a Wi-Fi security standard in September 17, 1999.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] The first versions of WEP were not particularly strong, even for the time they were released, due to U.S. restrictions on the export of various cryptographic technologies.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] These restrictions led to manufacturers restricting their devices to only 64-bit encryption.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] When the restrictions were lifted, the encryption was increased to 128 bits.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] Despite the introduction of 256-bit WEP, 128-bit remains one of the most common implementations.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] WEP was included as the privacy component of the original IEEE 802.11 standard ratified in 1997.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] WEP uses the stream cipher RC4 for confidentiality, and the CRC-32 checksum for integrity.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] It was deprecated in 2004 and is documented in the current standard.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] Standard 64-bit WEP uses a 40-bit key (also known as WEP-40), which is concatenated with a 24-bit initialization vector (IV) to form the RC4 key.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] At the time that the original WEP standard was drafted, the U.S.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] Government's export restrictions on cryptographic technology limited the key size.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] Once the restrictions were lifted, manufacturers of access points implemented an extended 128-bit WEP protocol using a 104-bit key size (WEP-104).
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] A 64-bit WEP key is usually entered as a string of 10 hexadecimal (base 16) characters (0–9 and A–F).
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] Each character represents 4 bits, 10 digits of 4 bits each gives 40 bits; adding the 24-bit IV produces the complete 64-bit WEP key (4 bits × 10 + 24-bit IV = 64-bit WEP key).
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] A 128-bit WEP key is usually entered as a string of 26 hexadecimal characters.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] 26 digits of 4 bits each gives 104 bits; adding the 24-bit IV produces the complete 128-bit WEP key (4 bits × 26 + 24-bit IV = 128-bit WEP key).
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] Most devices also allow the user to enter it as 13 ASCII characters (8 bits × 13 + 24-bit IV = 128-bit WEP key).
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] 152-bit and 256-bit WEP systems are available from some vendors.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] As with the other WEP variants, 24 bits of that is for the IV, leaving 128 or 232 bits for actual protection.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] These 128 or 232 bits are typically entered as 32 or 58 hexadecimal characters (4 bits × 32 + 24-bit IV = 152-bit WEP key, 4 bits × 58 + 24-bit IV = 256-bit WEP key).
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] Most devices also allow the user to enter it as 16 or 29 ASCII characters (8 bits × 16 + 24-bit IV = 152-bit WEP key, 8 bits × 29 + 24-bit IV = 256-bit WEP key).
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] Two methods of authentication can be used with WEP: Open System authentication and Shared Key authentication.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] In Open System authentication, the WLAN client does not provide its credentials to the access point during authentication.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] Any client can authenticate with the access point and then attempt to associate.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] Subsequently, WEP keys can be used for encrypting data frames.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] At this point, the client must have the correct keys.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] The access point replies with a clear-text challenge.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] The client encrypts the challenge-text using the configured WEP key and sends it back in another authentication request.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] If this matches the challenge text, the access point sends back a positive reply.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] After the authentication and association, the pre-shared WEP key is also used for encrypting the data frames using RC4.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] At first glance, it might seem as though Shared Key authentication is more secure than Open System authentication since the latter offers no real authentication.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] It is possible to derive the keystream used for the handshake by capturing the challenge frames in Shared Key authentication.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] Therefore, data can be more easily intercepted and decrypted with Shared Key authentication than with Open System authentication.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] If privacy is a primary concern, it is more advisable to use Open System authentication for WEP authentication, rather than Shared Key authentication; however, this also means that any WLAN client can connect to the AP.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] Because RC4 is a stream cipher, the same traffic key must never be used twice.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] The purpose of an IV, which is transmitted as plaintext, is to prevent any repetition, but a 24-bit IV is not long enough to ensure this on a busy network.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] The way the IV was used also opened WEP to a related-key attack.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] For a 24-bit IV, there is a 50% probability the same IV will repeat after 5,000 packets.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] In August 2001, Scott Fluhrer, Itsik Mantin, and Adi Shamir published a cryptanalysis of WEP that exploits the way the RC4 ciphers and IV are used in WEP, resulting in a passive attack that can recover the RC4 key after eavesdropping on the network.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] Depending on the amount of network traffic, and thus the number of packets available for inspection, a successful key recovery could take as little as one minute.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] If an insufficient number of packets are being sent, there are ways for an attacker to send packets on the network and thereby stimulate reply packets, which can then be inspected to find the key.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] The attack was soon implemented, and automated tools have since been released.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] It is possible to perform the attack with a personal computer, off-the-shelf hardware, and freely available software such as aircrack-ng to crack *any* WEP key in minutes.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] Cam-Winget et al. surveyed a variety of shortcomings in WEP.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] Federal Bureau of Investigation gave a demonstration where they cracked a WEP-protected network in three minutes using publicly available tools.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] Andreas Klein presented another analysis of the RC4 stream cipher.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] Klein showed that there are more correlations between the RC4 keystream and the key than the ones found by Fluhrer, Mantin, and Shamir, which can additionally be used to break WEP in WEP-like usage modes.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] In 2006, Bittau, Handley, and Lackey showed that the 802.11 protocol itself can be used against WEP to enable earlier attacks that were previously thought impractical.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] After eavesdropping a single packet, an attacker can rapidly bootstrap to be able to transmit arbitrary data.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] The eavesdropped packet can then be decrypted one byte at a time (by transmitting about 128 packets per byte to decrypt) to discover the local network IP addresses.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] Finally, if the 802.11 network is connected to the Internet, the attacker can use 802.11 fragmentation to replay eavesdropped packets while crafting a new IP header onto them.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] The access point can then be used to decrypt these packets and relay them on to a buddy on the Internet, allowing real-time decryption of WEP traffic within a minute of eavesdropping the first packet.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] In 2007, Erik Tews, Andrei Pyshkin, and Ralf-Philipp Weinmann were able to extend Klein's 2005 attack and optimize it for usage against WEP.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] With the new attack it is possible to recover a 104-bit WEP key with a probability of 50% using only 40,000 captured packets.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] For 60,000 available data packets, the success probability is about 80%, and for 85,000 data packets, about 95%.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] Using active techniques like Wi-Fi deauthentication attacks and ARP re-injection, 40,000 packets can be captured in less than one minute under good conditions.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] The actual computation takes about 3 seconds and 3 MB of main memory on a Pentium-M 1.7 GHz and can additionally be optimized for devices with slower CPUs.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] The same attack can be used for 40-bit keys with an even higher success probability.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] In 2008 the Payment Card Industry Security Standards Council (PCI SSC) updated the Data Security Standard (DSS) to prohibit use of WEP as part of any credit-card processing after 30 June 2010, and prohibit any new system from being installed that uses WEP after 31 March 2009.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] The use of WEP contributed to the TJ Maxx parent company network invasion.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] The Caffe Latte attack is another way to defeat WEP.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] It is not necessary for the attacker to be in the area of the network using this exploit.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] By using a process that targets the Windows wireless stack, it is possible to obtain the WEP key from a remote client.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] By sending a flood of encrypted ARP requests, the assailant takes advantage of the shared key authentication and the message modification flaws in 802.11 WEP.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] The attacker uses the ARP responses to obtain the WEP key in less than 6 minutes.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] Use of encrypted tunneling protocols (e.g., IPsec, Secure Shell) can provide secure data transmission over an insecure network.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] However, replacements for WEP have been developed with the goal of restoring security to the wireless network itself.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] The recommended solution to WEP security problems is to switch to WPA2.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] WPA was an intermediate solution for hardware that could not support WPA2.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] Both WPA and WPA2 are much more secure than WEP.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] To add support for WPA or WPA2, some old Wi-Fi access points might need to be replaced or have their firmware upgraded.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] WPA was designed as an interim software-implementable solution for WEP that could forestall immediate deployment of new hardware.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] However, TKIP (the basis of WPA) has reached the end of its designed lifetime, has been partially broken, and has been officially deprecated with the release of the 802.11-2012 standard.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] This stopgap enhancement to WEP was present in some of the early 802.11i drafts.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] It was implementable on *some* (not all) hardware not able to handle WPA or WPA2, and extended both the IV and the key values to 128 bits.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] It was hoped to eliminate the duplicate IV deficiency as well as stop brute-force key attacks.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] After it became clear that the overall WEP algorithm was deficient (and not just the IV and key sizes) and would require even more fixes, both the WEP2 name and original algorithm were dropped.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] The two extended key lengths remained in what eventually became WPA's TKIP.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] WEPplus, also known as WEP+, is a proprietary enhancement to WEP by Agere Systems (formerly a subsidiary of Lucent Technologies) that enhances WEP security by avoiding "weak IVs".
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] It is only completely effective when WEPplus is used at *both ends* of the wireless connection.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] As this cannot easily be enforced, it remains a serious limitation.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] It also does not necessarily prevent replay attacks, and is ineffective against later statistical attacks that do not rely on weak IVs.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] Dynamic WEP refers to the combination of 802.1x technology and the Extensible Authentication Protocol.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] Dynamic WEP changes WEP keys dynamically.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] It is a vendor-specific feature provided by several vendors such as 3Com.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wired-equivalent-privacy] The dynamic change idea made it into 802.11i as part of TKIP, but not for the WEP protocol itself.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Many laptop computers have wireless cards pre-installed.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] The ability to enter a network while mobile has great benefits.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] However, wireless networking is prone to some security issues.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Hackers have found wireless networks relatively easy to break into, and even use wireless technology to hack into wired networks.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] As a result, it is very important that enterprises define effective wireless security policies that guard against unauthorized access to important resources.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Wireless Intrusion Prevention Systems (WIPS) or Wireless Intrusion Detection Systems (WIDS) are commonly used to enforce wireless security policies.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] The risks to users of wireless technology have increased as the service has become more popular.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] There were relatively few dangers when wireless technology was first introduced.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Hackers had not yet had time to latch on to the new technology, and wireless networks were not commonly found in the work place.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] However, there are many security risks associated with the current wireless protocols and encryption methods, and in the carelessness and ignorance that exists at the user and corporate IT level.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Hacking methods have become much more sophisticated and innovative with wireless access.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Hacking has also become much easier and more accessible with easy-to-use Windows- or Linux-based tools being made available on the web at no charge.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Some organizations that have no wireless access points installed do not feel that they need to address wireless security concerns.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] In-Stat MDR and META Group have estimated that 95% of all corporate laptop computers that were planned to be purchased in 2005 were equipped with wireless cards.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Issues can arise in a supposedly non-wireless organization when a wireless laptop is plugged into the corporate network.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] A hacker could sit out in the parking lot and gather information from it through laptops and/or other devices, or even break in through this wireless card–equipped laptop and gain access to the wired network.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Anyone within the geographical network range of an open, unencrypted wireless network can "sniff", or capture and record, the traffic, gain unauthorized access to internal network resources as well as to the internet, and then use the information and resources to perform disruptive or illegal acts.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Such security breaches have become important concerns for both enterprise and home networks.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] If router security is not activated or if the owner deactivates it for convenience, it creates a free hotspot.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Since most 21st-century laptop PCs have wireless networking built in (see Intel "Centrino" technology), they do not need a third-party adapter such as a PCMCIA Card or USB dongle.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Built-in wireless networking might be enabled by default, without the owner realizing it, thus broadcasting the laptop's accessibility to any computer nearby.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Modern operating systems such as Linux, macOS, or Microsoft Windows make it fairly easy to set up a PC as a wireless LAN "base station" using Internet Connection Sharing, thus allowing all the PCs in the home to access the Internet through the "base" PC.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] However, lack of knowledge among users about the security issues inherent in setting up such systems often may allow others nearby access to the connection.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Such "piggybacking" is usually achieved without the wireless network operator's knowledge; it may even be without the knowledge of the intruding user if their computer automatically selects a nearby unsecured wireless network to use as an access point.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Wireless security is another aspect of computer security.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Organizations may be particularly vulnerable to security breaches caused by rogue access points.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] If an employee adds a wireless interface to an unsecured port of a system, they may create a breach in network security that would allow access to confidential materials.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Countermeasures like disabling open switchports during switch configuration and VLAN configuration to limit network access are available to protect the network and the information it contains, but such countermeasures must be applied uniformly to all network devices.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Wireless communication is useful in industrial machine to machine (M2M) communication.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Such industrial applications often have specific security requirements.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Evaluation of these vulnerabilities and the resulting vulnerability catalogs in an industrial context when considering WLAN, NFC and ZigBee are available.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] The modes of unauthorised access to links, to functions and to data is as variable as the respective entities make use of program code.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] There does not exist a full scope model of such threat.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] To some extent the prevention relies on known modes and methods of attack and relevant methods for suppression of the applied methods.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] However, each new mode of operation will create new options of threatening.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Hence prevention requires a steady drive for improvement.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] The described modes of attack are just a snapshot of typical methods and scenarios where to apply.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Violation of the security perimeter of a corporate network can come from a number of different methods and intents.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] One of these methods is referred to as “accidental association”.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] When a user turns on a computer and it latches on to a wireless access point from a neighboring company's overlapping network, the user may not even know that this has occurred.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] However, it is a security breach in that proprietary company information is exposed and now there could exist a link from one company to the other.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] This is especially true if the laptop is also hooked to a wired network.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Accidental association is a case of wireless vulnerability called as "mis-association".
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Mis-association can be accidental, deliberate (for example, done to bypass corporate firewall) or it can result from deliberate attempts on wireless clients to lure them into connecting to attacker's APs.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] “Malicious associations” are when wireless devices can be actively made by attackers to connect to a company network through their laptop instead of a company access point (AP).
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] These types of laptops are known as “soft APs” and are created when a cyber criminal runs some software that makes their wireless network card look like a legitimate access point.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Once the thief has gained access, they can steal passwords, launch attacks on the wired network, or plant trojans.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Since wireless networks operate at the Layer 2 level, Layer 3 protections such as network authentication and virtual private networks (VPNs) offer no barrier.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Wireless 802.1X authentications do help with some protection but are still vulnerable to hacking.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] The idea behind this type of attack may not be to break into a VPN or other security measures.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Most likely the criminal is just trying to take over the client at the Layer 2 level.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Ad hoc networks can pose a security threat.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Ad hoc networks are defined as [peer to peer] networks between wireless computers that do not have an access point in between them.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] While these types of networks usually have little protection, encryption methods can be used to provide security.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] The security hole provided by Ad hoc networking is not the Ad hoc network itself but the bridge it provides into other networks, usually in the corporate environment, and the unfortunate default settings in most versions of Microsoft Windows to have this feature turned on unless explicitly disabled.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Thus the user may not even know they have an unsecured Ad hoc network in operation on their computer.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] If they are also using a wired or wireless infrastructure network at the same time, they are providing a bridge to the secured organizational network through the unsecured Ad hoc connection.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] A direct bridge, which requires the user actually configure a bridge between the two connections and is thus unlikely to be initiated unless explicitly desired, and an indirect bridge which is the shared resources on the user computer.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] The indirect bridge may expose private data that is shared from the user's computer to LAN connections, such as shared folders or private Network Attached Storage, making no distinction between authenticated or private connections and unauthenticated Ad-Hoc networks.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] This presents no threats not already familiar to open/public or unsecured wifi access points, but firewall rules may be circumvented in the case of poorly configured operating systems or local settings.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Non-traditional networks such as personal network Bluetooth devices are not safe from hacking and should be regarded as a security risk.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Even barcode readers, handheld PDAs, and wireless printers and copiers should be secured.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] These non-traditional networks can be easily overlooked by IT personnel who have narrowly focused on laptops and access points.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Identity theft (or MAC spoofing) occurs when a hacker is able to listen in on network traffic and identify the MAC address of a computer with network privileges.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Most wireless systems allow some kind of MAC filtering to allow only authorized computers with specific MAC IDs to gain access and utilize the network.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] However, programs exist that have network “sniffing” capabilities.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Combine these programs with other software that allow a computer to pretend it has any MAC address that the hacker desires, and the hacker can easily get around that hurdle.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] MAC filtering is effective only for small residential (SOHO) networks, since it provides protection only when the wireless device is "off the air".
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Any 802.11 device "on the air" freely transmits its unencrypted MAC address in its 802.11 headers, and it requires no special equipment or software to detect it.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Anyone with an 802.11 receiver (laptop and wireless adapter) and a freeware wireless packet analyzer can obtain the MAC address of any transmitting 802.11 within range.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] A man-in-the-middle attacker entices computers to log into a computer which is set up as a soft AP (Access Point).
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Once this is done, the hacker connects to a real access point through another wireless card offering a steady flow of traffic through the transparent hacking computer to the real network.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] One type of man-in-the-middle attack relies on security faults in challenge and handshake protocols to execute a “de-authentication attack”.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] This attack forces AP-connected computers to drop their connections and reconnect with the hacker's soft AP (disconnects the user from the modem so they have to connect again using their password which one can extract from the recording of the event).
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Man-in-the-middle attacks are enhanced by software such as LANjack and AirJack which automate multiple steps of the process, meaning what once required some skill can now be done by script kiddies.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Hotspots are particularly vulnerable to any attack since there is little to no security on these networks.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] A Denial-of-service attack (DoS) occurs when an attacker continually bombards a targeted AP (Access Point) or network with bogus requests, premature successful connection messages, failure messages, and/or other commands.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] These cause legitimate users to not be able to get on the network and may even cause the network to crash.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] These attacks rely on the abuse of protocols such as the Extensible Authentication Protocol (EAP).
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] The DoS attack in itself does little to expose organizational data to a malicious attacker, since the interruption of the network prevents the flow of data and actually indirectly protects data by preventing it from being transmitted.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] This works best on weakly encrypted systems such as WEP, where there are a number of tools available which can launch a dictionary style attack of "possibly accepted" security keys based on the "model" security key captured during the network recovery.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] In a network injection attack, a hacker can make use of access points that are exposed to non-filtered network traffic, specifically broadcasting network traffic such as Spanning Tree Protocol (802.1D), OSPF, RIP, and HSRP.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] The hacker injects bogus networking re-configuration commands that affect routers, switches, and intelligent hubs.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] A whole network can be brought down in this manner and require rebooting or even reprogramming of all intelligent networking devices.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] The Caffe Latte attack is another way to obtain a WEP key and does not require a nearby access point for the target network.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] The Caffe Latte attack works by tricking a client with the WEP password stored to connect to a malicious access point with the same SSID as the target network.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] After the client connects, the client generates ARP requests, which the malicious access point uses to obtain keystream data.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] The malicious access point then repeatedly sends a deauthentication packet to the client, causing the client to disconnect, reconnect, and send additional ARP requests, which the malicious access point then uses to obtain additional keystream data.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Once the malicious access point has collected a sufficient amount of keystream data. the WEP key can be cracked with a tool like [aircrack-ng].
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] The Caffe Latte attack was demonstrated against the Windows wireless stack, but other operating systems may also be vulnerable.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] The attack was named the "Caffe Latte" attack by researcher Vivek Ramachandran because it could be used to obtain the WEP key from a remote traveler in less than the 6 minutes it takes to drink a cup of coffee.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] There are three principal ways to secure a wireless network.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] There is no ready designed system to prevent from fraudulent usage of wireless communication or to protect data and functions with wirelessly communicating computers and other entities.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] However, there is a system of qualifying the taken measures as a whole according to a common understanding what shall be seen as state of the art.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] The system of qualifying is an international consensus as specified in ISO/IEC 15408.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] A Wireless Intrusion Prevention System (WIPS) is a concept for the most robust way to counteract wireless security risks.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] However such WIPS does not exist as a ready designed solution to implement as a software package.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] A WIPS is typically implemented as an overlay to an existing Wireless LAN infrastructure, although it may be deployed standalone to enforce no-wireless policies within an organization.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] WIPS is considered so important to wireless security that in July 2009, the Payment Card Industry Security Standards Council published wireless guidelines for PCI DSS recommending the use of WIPS to automate wireless scanning and protection for large organizations.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Several WIPS vendors were established in the early 2000s.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] AirDefense was founded in 2001 and later acquired by Motorola in 2008.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Mojo Networks was founded in 2004 and later acquired by Arista Networks in 2018.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] With the rapid growth of Wireless LANs, WIPS became an important part of every organization's security posture.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] There are a range of wireless security measures, of varying effectiveness and practicality.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] A simple but ineffective method to attempt to secure a wireless network is to hide the SSID (Service Set Identifier).
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] This provides very little protection against anything but the most casual intrusion efforts.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] One of the simplest techniques is to only allow access from known, pre-approved MAC addresses.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Most wireless access points contain some type of MAC ID filtering.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] However, an attacker can simply sniff the MAC address of an authorized client and spoof this address.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Typical wireless access points provide IP addresses to clients via DHCP.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Requiring clients to set their own addresses makes it more difficult for a casual or unsophisticated intruder to log onto the network, but provides little protection against a sophisticated attacker.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] IEEE 802.1X is the IEEE Standard authentication mechanisms to devices wishing to attach to a Wireless LAN.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] The Wired Equivalent Privacy (WEP) encryption standard was the original encryption standard for wireless, but since 2004 with the ratification WPA2 the IEEE has declared it "deprecated", and while often supported, it is seldom or never the default on modern equipment.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Concerns were raised about its security as early as 2001, dramatically demonstrated in 2005 by the FBI, yet in 2007 T.J.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Maxx admitted a massive security breach due in part to a reliance on WEP and the Payment Card Industry took until 2008 to prohibit its use – and even then allowed existing use to continue until June 2010.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] The Wi-Fi Protected Access (WPA and WPA2) security protocols were later created to address the problems with WEP.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] If a weak password, such as a dictionary word or short character string is used, WPA and WPA2 can be cracked.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Using a long enough random password (e.g.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] 5 randomly chosen words) makes pre-shared key WPA virtually uncrackable.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] The second generation of the WPA security protocol (WPA2) is based on the final IEEE 802.11i amendment to the 802.11 standard and is eligible for FIPS 140-2 compliance.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] With all those encryption schemes, any client in the network that knows the keys can read all the traffic.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Wi-Fi Protected Access (WPA) is a software/firmware improvement over WEP.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] All regular WLAN-equipment that worked with WEP are able to be simply upgraded and no new equipment needs to be bought.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] WPA is a trimmed-down version of the 802.11i security standard that was developed by the IEEE 802.11 to replace WEP.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] The TKIP encryption algorithm was developed for WPA to provide improvements to WEP that could be fielded as firmware upgrades to existing 802.11 devices.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] The WPA profile also provides optional support for the AES-CCMP algorithm that is the preferred algorithm in 802.11i and WPA2.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] WPA Enterprise provides RADIUS based authentication using 802.1X.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] WPA Personal uses a pre-shared Shared Key (PSK) to establish the security using an 8 to 63 character passphrase.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] The PSK may also be entered as a 64 character hexadecimal string.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Weak PSK passphrases can be broken using off-line dictionary attacks by capturing the messages in the four-way exchange when the client reconnects after being deauthenticated.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Wireless suites such as aircrack-ng can crack a weak passphrase in less than a minute.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Other WEP/WPA crackers are AirSnort and Auditor Security Collection.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Still, WPA Personal is secure when used with ‘good’ passphrases or a full 64-character hexadecimal key.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] There was information, however, that Erik Tews (the man who created the fragmentation attack against WEP) was going to reveal a way of breaking the WPA TKIP implementation at Tokyo's PacSec security conference in November 2008, cracking the encryption on a packet in 12 to 15 minutes.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] In addition to WPAv1, TKIP, WIDS and EAP may be added alongside.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Also, VPN-networks (non-continuous secure network connections) may be set up under the 802.11-standard.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] VPN implementations include PPTP, L2TP, IPsec and SSH.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] However, this extra layer of security may also be cracked with tools such as Anger, Deceit and Ettercap for PPTP; and ike-scan, IKEProbe, ipsectrace, and IKEcrack for IPsec-connections.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] This stands for Temporal Key Integrity Protocol and the acronym is pronounced as tee-kip.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] This is part of the IEEE 802.11i standard.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] TKIP implements per-packet key mixing with a re-keying system and also provides a message integrity check.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] The WPA-improvement over the IEEE 802.1X standard already improved the authentication and authorization for access of wireless and wired LANs.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] In addition to this, extra measures such as the Extensible Authentication Protocol (EAP) have initiated an even greater amount of security.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] This, as EAP uses a central authentication server.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Unfortunately, during 2002 a Maryland professor discovered some shortcomings .
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Over the next few years these shortcomings were addressed with the use of TLS and other enhancements.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] This new version of EAP is now called Extended EAP and is available in several versions; these include: EAP-MD5, PEAPv0, PEAPv1, EAP-MSCHAPv2, LEAP, EAP-FAST, EAP-TLS, EAP-TTLS, MSCHAPv2, and EAP-SIM.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] EAP-versions include LEAP, PEAP and other EAP's.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] This stands for the Lightweight Extensible Authentication Protocol.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] This protocol is based on 802.1X and helps minimize the original security flaws by using WEP and a sophisticated key management system.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] This also uses MAC address authentication.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] LEAP is not secure; THC-LeapCracker can be used to break Cisco's version of LEAP and be used against computers connected to an access point in the form of a dictionary attack.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Anwrap and asleap finally are other crackers capable of breaking LEAP.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] This stands for Protected Extensible Authentication Protocol.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] This protocol allows for a secure transport of data, passwords, and encryption keys without the need of a certificate server.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] This was developed by Cisco, Microsoft, and RSA Security.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Solutions include a newer system for authentication, IEEE 802.1X, that promises to enhance security on both wired and wireless networks.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Wireless access points that incorporate technologies like these often also have routers built in, thus becoming wireless gateways.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] One can argue that both layer 2 and layer 3 encryption methods are not good enough for protecting valuable data like passwords and personal emails.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Those technologies add encryption only to parts of the communication path, still allowing people to spy on the traffic if they have gained access to the wired network somehow.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] The solution may be encryption and authorization in the application layer, using technologies like SSL, SSH, GnuPG, PGP and similar.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] The disadvantage with the end-to-end method is, it may fail to cover all traffic.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] With encryption on the router level or VPN, a single switch encrypts all traffic, even UDP and DNS lookups.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] With end-to-end encryption on the other hand, each service to be secured must have its encryption "turned on", and often every connection must also be "turned on" separately.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] For sending emails, every recipient must support the encryption method, and must exchange keys correctly.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] For Web, not all web sites offer https, and even if they do, the browser sends out IP addresses in clear text.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] The most prized resource is often access to the Internet.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] An office LAN owner seeking to restrict such access will face the nontrivial enforcement task of having each user authenticate themselves for the router.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] The newest and most rigorous security to implement into WLAN's today is the 802.11i RSN-standard.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] This full-fledged 802.11i standard (which uses WPAv2) however does require the newest hardware (unlike WPAv1), thus potentially requiring the purchase of new equipment.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] This new hardware required may be either AES-WRAP (an early version of 802.11i) or the newer and better AES-CCMP-equipment.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] One should make sure one needs WRAP or CCMP-equipment, as the 2 hardware standards are not compatible.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] WPA2 is a WiFi Alliance branded version of the final 802.11i standard.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] The primary enhancement over WPA is the inclusion of the AES-CCMP algorithm as a mandatory feature.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Both WPA and WPA2 support EAP authentication methods using RADIUS servers and preshared key (PSK).
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] The number of WPA and WPA2 networks are increasing, while the number of WEP networks are decreasing, because of the security vulnerabilities in WEP.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] WPA2 has been found to have at least one security vulnerability, nicknamed Hole196.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] The vulnerability uses the WPA2 Group Temporal Key (GTK), which is a shared key among all users of the same BSSID, to launch attacks on other users of the same BSSID.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] It is named after page 196 of the IEEE 802.11i specification, where the vulnerability is discussed.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] In order for this exploit to be performed, the GTK must be known by the attacker.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Unlike 802.1X, 802.11i already has most other additional security-services such as TKIP.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Just as with WPAv1, WPAv2 may work in cooperation with EAP and a WIDS.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] This stands for WLAN Authentication and Privacy Infrastructure.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] This is a wireless security standard defined by the Chinese government.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Security token use is a method of authentication relying upon only authorized users possessing the requisite token.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Smart cards are physical tokens in the cards that utilize an embedded integrated circuit chip for authentication, requiring a card reader.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] USB Tokens are physical tokens that connect via USB port to authenticate the user.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] It is practical in some cases to apply specialized wall paint and window film to a room or building to significantly attenuate wireless signals, which keeps the signals from propagating outside a facility.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] This can significantly improve wireless security because it is difficult for hackers to receive the signals beyond the controlled area of a facility, such as from a parking lot.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] However, a lot of them are difficult to stop even after detection.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Here are three of the most common ways to stop a DoS attack.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Black holing is one possible way of stopping a DoS attack.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] This is a situation where we drop all IP packets from an attacker.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] This is not a very good long-term strategy because attackers can change their source address very quickly.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] This may have negative effects if done automatically.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] An attacker could knowingly spoof attack packets with the IP address of a corporate partner.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Automated defenses could block legitimate traffic from that partner and cause additional problems.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Validating the handshake involves creating false opens, and not setting aside resources until the sender acknowledges.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Some firewalls address SYN floods by pre-validating the TCP handshake.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Whenever a SYN segment arrives, the firewall sends back a SYN/ACK segment, without passing the SYN segment on to the target server.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Only when the firewall gets back an ACK, which would happen only in a legitimate connection, would the firewall send the original SYN segment on to the server for which it was originally intended.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] The firewall does not set aside resources for a connection when a SYN segment arrives, so handling a large number of false SYN segments is only a small burden.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Rate limiting can be used to reduce a certain type of traffic down to an amount the can be reasonably dealt with.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Broadcasting to the internal network could still be used, but only at a limited rate for example.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] This is good if an attack is aimed at a single server because it keeps transmission lines at least partially open for other communication.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Rate limiting frustrates both the attacker, and the legitimate users.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] This helps but does not fully solve the problem.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Once DoS traffic clogs the access line going to the internet, there is nothing a border firewall can do to help the situation.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Most DoS attacks are problems of the community which can only be stopped with the help of ISP's and organizations whose computers are taken over as bots and used to attack other firms.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] With increasing number of mobile devices with 802.1X interfaces, security of such mobile devices becomes a concern.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] While open standards such as Kismet are targeted towards securing laptops, access points solutions should extend towards covering mobile devices also.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Host based solutions for mobile handsets and PDA's with 802.1X interface.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Wireless IPS solutions now offer wireless security for mobile devices.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Mobile patient monitoring devices are becoming an integral part of healthcare industry and these devices will eventually become the method of choice for accessing and implementing health checks for patients located in remote areas.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] For these types of patient monitoring systems, security and reliability are critical, because they can influence the condition of patients, and could leave medical professionals in the dark about the condition of the patient if compromised.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] In order to implement 802.11i, one must first make sure both that the router/access point(s), as well as all client devices are indeed equipped to support the network encryption.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] If this is done, a server such as RADIUS, ADS, NDS, or LDAP needs to be integrated.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] This server can be a computer on the local network, an access point / router with integrated authentication server, or a remote server.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] AP's/routers with integrated authentication servers are often very expensive and specifically an option for commercial usage like hot spots.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Hosted 802.1X servers via the Internet require a monthly fee; running a private server is free yet has the disadvantage that one must set it up and that the server needs to be on continuously.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] To set up a server, server and client software must be installed.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Server software required is an enterprise authentication server such as RADIUS, ADS, NDS, or LDAP.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] The required software can be picked from various suppliers as Microsoft, Cisco, Funk Software, Meetinghouse Data, and from some open-source projects.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Today, there is almost full wireless network coverage in many urban areas – the infrastructure for the wireless community network (which some consider to be the future of the internet ) is already in place.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] One could roam around and always be connected to Internet if the nodes were open to the public, but due to security concerns, most nodes are encrypted and the users do not know how to disable encryption.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Many people consider it proper etiquette to leave access points open to the public, allowing free access to Internet.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Others think the default encryption provides substantial protection at small inconvenience, against dangers of open access that they fear may be substantial even on a home DSL router.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] The density of access points can even be a problem – there are a limited number of channels available, and they partly overlap.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Each channel can handle multiple networks, but places with many private wireless networks (for example, apartment complexes), the limited number of Wi-Fi radio channels might cause slowness and other problems.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] On the other hand, in some countries including Germany, persons providing an open access point may be made (partially) liable for any illegal activity conducted via this access point.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Also, many contracts with ISPs specify that the connection may not be shared with other persons.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Wireless network security is subject to regulatory mandates in industries handling sensitive data, as wireless access points expand the attack surface of protected information systems.
[src:wifi-security-wpa/wireless-security] Healthcare organizations must also implement access controls under 45 CFR 164.312(a)(1) and audit controls under 45 CFR 164.312(b) for all systems accessible via wireless networks.
